= Introduction to Bilateral Animals

- *Bilateral symmetry* (两侧对称): The body can be divided along only one plane of symmetry to yield two mirror-image halves.
- *Cephalization* (头部形成): Concentration of sense organs and nervous control centers on the head (anterior) end.
- *Triploblastic* (三胚层): Body derived from three germ layers: *ectoderm* (外胚层), *endoderm* (内胚层), and *mesoderm* (中胚层).
- *Acoelomate* (无体腔): Animals that lack a coelom (body cavity); the region between the epidermis and digestive cavity is filled with *parenchyma* (实质) (mesodermally derived packing tissue).
- *Protostomia* (原口动物): Clade of animals with spiral or centrolecithal cleavage, mosaic development, and the blastopore becoming the mouth.
- *Lophotrochozoa* (冠轮动物): A clade within Protostomia including Platyhelminthes, Nemertea, Mollusca, Annelida, etc., often sharing a *trochophore* (担轮幼虫) larva or *lophophore* (触手冠).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-1").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-1").caption
)
- *Acoelomate body plan*: As shown in the figure, the gut (endoderm) is surrounded by a solid mass of parenchyma (mesoderm), with no fluid-filled body cavity between the gut and the body wall (ectoderm).

= Phylum Acoelomorpha (无腔动物门)

- Small flatworms, less than 5 mm long, typically living in marine sediments.
- Formerly placed in class Turbellaria but now considered an early diverging bilateral group.
- *Statocysts* (平衡囊) differ in structure from those of platyhelminths.
- *Digestion*: Mouth leads to a tube-like pharynx and a sacklike gut (no anus). In many acoels, the gut is absent, and food is digested in a syncytial mass of endodermal cells.
- *Reproduction*: Monoecious; produce *endolecithal eggs* (内卵黄卵); exhibit a unique *duet-spiral cleavage* (二重螺旋卵裂) pattern.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-2").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-2").caption
)
- *Acoelomorphs*: These small worms, like *Waminoa*, are often found on corals or in sediments.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-3").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-3").caption
)
- *Acoelomorph structure*: The diagram illustrates the simple body plan with a mouth opening into a mass of endodermal cells rather than a distinct gut cavity in some forms.

= Phylum Platyhelminthes (扁形动物门)

- Bilaterally symmetrical, triploblastic, acoelomate animals.
- Flattened dorsoventrally.
- Divided into four classes: *Turbellaria* (涡虫纲) (mostly free-living), *Trematoda* (吸虫纲) (flukes), *Monogenea* (单殖吸虫纲) (monogenetic flukes), and *Cestoda* (绦虫纲) (tapeworms).
- *Neodermata* (新皮类): A clade containing the parasitic classes (Trematoda, Monogenea, Cestoda), characterized by a *syncytial tegument* (合胞体体壁/皮层) (neodermis).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-4").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-4").caption
)
- *Free-living flatworms*: Planarians (aquatic) and *Bipalium* (terrestrial) are examples of the class Turbellaria.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-5").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-5").caption
)
- *Phylogeny*: The cladogram shows that Turbellaria is paraphyletic. The parasitic groups (Trematoda, Monogenea, Cestoda) form a monophyletic clade called *Neodermata*, sharing the syncytial tegument.

== Form and Function

=== Epidermis and Muscles
- *Turbellaria*: Cellular, ciliated epidermis with *rhabdites* (杆状体) (rod-shaped structures that form a protective mucous sheath).
- *Dual-gland adhesive organs* (双腺粘附器官): Consist of viscid gland cells (fasten to substrate), releasing gland cells (detach), and anchor cells.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-6").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-6").caption
)
- *Planarian cross section*: Shows the ciliated epidermis, rhabdites, and the arrangement of circular, longitudinal, and parenchymal muscles.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-7").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-7").caption
)
- *Dual-gland organ*: Illustrates the mechanism of attachment and detachment in turbellarians using viscid and releasing glands.

- *Parasitic classes (Neodermata)*: Adults have a non-ciliated *syncytial tegument* (合胞体体壁) (neodermis).
- *Syncytial* (合胞体): Many nuclei enclosed within a single cell membrane.
- Tegument is resistant to host immune responses and digestive enzymes.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-8").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-8").caption
)
- *Tegument structure*: The syncytial tegument has cell bodies sunk beneath the muscle layer, connected to the surface cytoplasm by extensions.

=== Nutrition and Digestion
- Digestive system typically includes a mouth, pharynx, and intestine (incomplete gut, no anus).
- *Planarians*: Pharynx enclosed in a pharyngeal sheath; intestine has three branches (one anterior, two posterior).
- Digestion is both extracellular (in intestine) and intracellular (gastrodermal phagocytosis).
- *Cestodes*: Lack a digestive system; absorb nutrients through the tegument.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-9").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-9").caption
)
- *Planarian systems*:
    - *Digestive*: Three-branched intestine and extensible pharynx.
    - *Excretory*: Protonephridia with flame cells.
    - *Nervous*: Ladder-type system with anterior cerebral ganglia.
    - *Reproductive*: Monoecious with complex gonads and ducts.

=== Excretion and Osmoregulation
- *Protonephridia* (原肾管): Excretory/osmoregulatory organs with *flame cells* (焰细胞).
- *Flame cell*: Cup-shaped with a tuft of flagella driving fluid through a *weir* (堰) system into collecting ducts.
- Primarily osmoregulatory in freshwater forms; metabolic wastes largely removed by diffusion.

=== Nervous System and Sense Organs
- *Subepidermal nerve plexus* (表皮下神经丛) (primitive) or *longitudinal nerve cords* (纵神经索) (1-5 pairs).
- *Ladder-type nervous system* (梯状神经系统): Ventral nerve cords connected by transverse nerves.
- *Brain*: Bilobed mass of ganglion cells.
- *Sense organs*: *Ocelli* (眼点) (eyespots), tactile cells, chemoreceptors, *statocysts* (平衡囊) (equilibrium), *rheoreceptors* (流速感受器) (water current).

=== Reproduction
- Asexual reproduction: Fission (constriction behind pharynx) in planarians; budding in some tapeworms.
- Sexual reproduction: Most are *monoecious* (雌雄同体) (hermaphroditic) with cross-fertilization.
- *Endolecithal eggs* (内卵黄卵): Yolk contained within the egg cell (ancestral).
- *Ectolecithal eggs* (外卵黄卵): Yolk contributed by separate *vitellaria* (卵黄腺) (yolk glands); characteristic of Trematoda, Monogenea, Cestoda, and some Turbellaria.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-10").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-10").caption
)
- *Clonorchis reproductive system*: Shows the complex hermaphroditic system typical of flukes, including testes, ovary, uterus, seminal receptacle, and vitellaria.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-11").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-11").caption
)
- *Asexual reproduction*: Freshwater turbellarians like *Microstomum* and *Stenostomum* can reproduce by fission, forming chains of zooids.

== Class Turbellaria (涡虫纲)

- Mostly free-living; marine, freshwater, or terrestrial.
- Distinguished by gut form and pharynx type.
- *Polycladida* (多肠目): Folded pharynx, highly branched intestine (marine).
- *Tricladida* (三肠目): Three-branched intestine (freshwater planarians).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-12").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-12").caption
)
- *Intestinal patterns*: Comparison of the three-branched intestine of Tricladida and the multi-branched intestine of Polycladida.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-13").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-13").caption
)
- *Marine polyclad*: *Pseudobiceros* displays the vibrant colors and flat body typical of marine polyclads.

== Class Trematoda (吸虫纲)

- All parasitic flukes; adults are endoparasites of vertebrates.
- Leaflike body with suckers (oral and ventral) but no hooks (unlike Monogenea).
- *Subclass Digenea* (复殖亚纲): Complex life cycle with an intermediate host (mollusc) and a definitive host (vertebrate).

=== Life Cycle Stages
1.  *Egg*: Shelled embryo passed in feces.
2.  *Miracidium* (毛蚴): Free-swimming ciliated larva; penetrates snail.
3.  *Sporocyst* (胞蚴): Sac-like asexual stage in snail.
4.  *Redia* (雷蚴): Asexual stage with a gut; produces more rediae or cercariae.
5.  *Cercaria* (尾蚴): Free-swimming larva emerging from snail.
6.  *Metacercaria* (囊蚴): Encysted juvenile fluke (infective stage).
7.  *Adult*: Sexual stage in definitive host.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-14").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-14").caption
)
- *Clonorchis life cycle*: Egg $->$ Snail (Miracidium $->$ Sporocyst $->$ Redia $->$ Cercaria) $->$ Fish (Metacercaria) $->$ Human (Adult in liver bile duct).

#figure(
  image(images.at("table-14-1").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("table-14-1").caption
)
- *Human flukes*: Table lists important species like *Schistosoma*, *Clonorchis*, *Paragonimus*, and *Fasciolopsis*, their distribution, and means of infection.

=== Important Trematodes
- *Clonorchis sinensis* (华支睾吸虫/肝吸虫) (Chinese liver fluke): Infection via raw fish.
- *Schistosoma* (血吸虫) (Blood flukes): Dioecious (separate sexes); male has *gynecophoric canal* (抱雌沟). Infection via cercariae penetrating skin. No metacercaria stage.
    - *S. mansoni*: Large intestine veins.
    - *S. japonicum*: Small intestine veins.
    - *S. haematobium*: Urinary bladder veins.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-15").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-15").caption
)
- *Schistosoma*:
    - A: Male holding female in gynecophoric canal.
    - B: Life cycle involving snail host and direct skin penetration by cercariae.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-16").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-16").caption
)
- *Pathology*: Schistosomiasis can cause severe liver fibrosis due to immune reaction against eggs trapped in tissues.

- *Paragonimus westermani* (卫氏并殖吸虫/肺吸虫) (Lung fluke): Infection via raw crabs/crayfish.
- *Leucochloridium* (彩蚴吸虫): Sporocysts enter snail tentacles and pulsate to attract bird hosts.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-17").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-17").caption
)
- *Paragonimus*: Adult fluke lives in lungs; eggs coughed up or swallowed.

== Class Monogenea (单殖吸虫纲)

- Ectoparasites, primarily on fish gills and skin.
- Direct life cycle (single host).
- *Opisthaptor* (后吸器): Large posterior attachment organ with hooks, suckers, or clamps.
- *Oncomiracidium* (钩毛蚴): Ciliated larva.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-18").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-18").caption
)
- *Monogenean structure*: *Gyrodactylus* showing the opisthaptor with hooks for attachment to the host.

== Class Cestoda (绦虫纲)

- Endoparasites in vertebrate digestive tracts.
- Long, flat body composed of:
    - *Scolex* (头节): Holdfast organ with suckers/hooks.
    - *Neck* (颈部): Germinative zone.
    - *Strobila* (链体): Chain of *proglottids* (节片) (reproductive units).
- No digestive system.
- *Microtriches* (微毛): Minute projections on tegument to increase surface area for absorption.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-19").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-19").caption
)
- *Tapeworm body plan*: Scolex for attachment, followed by a strobila of immature, mature, and gravid proglottids.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-20").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-20").caption
)
- *Tegument sensory ending*: Shows the microtriches (microvilli-like) and a sensory cilium.

#figure(
  image(images.at("table-14-2").path, width: 80%),
  caption: images.at("table-14-2").caption
)
- *Human Cestodes*: Lists *Taenia saginata*, *Taenia solium*, *Diphyllobothrium latum*, *Echinococcus granulosus*, etc.

=== Important Cestodes
- *Taenia saginata* (牛带绦虫) (Beef tapeworm): Scolex with 4 suckers, no hooks. Cysticerci in cattle muscle ("measly beef").
- *Taenia solium* (猪带绦虫) (Pork tapeworm): Scolex with suckers and hooks (*rostellum* (顶突)). Cysticerci in pig muscle. Dangerous because humans can serve as intermediate hosts (*cysticercosis* (囊尾蚴病)).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-21").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-21").caption
)
- *Taenia saginata life cycle*: Human (definitive host) $->$ Eggs in feces $->$ Cattle (intermediate host) $->$ Cysticercus in muscle $->$ Human eats rare beef.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-22").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-22").caption
)
- *Mature proglottid*: Contains complete male (testes, vas deferens) and female (ovary, uterus, vitelline gland) reproductive systems.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-23").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-23").caption
)
- *Cysticercosis*: Brain section showing infection with *Taenia solium* cysticerci, a potentially fatal condition.

- *Diphyllobothrium latum* (阔节裂头绦虫) (Fish tapeworm): Largest cestode infecting humans; can cause anemia.
- *Echinococcus granulosus* (细粒棘球绦虫) (Dog tapeworm): Causes *hydatidosis* (棘球蚴病) (hydatid cysts) in humans (intermediate host).

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-24").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-24").caption
)
- *Echinococcus*:
    - A: Hydatid cyst with brood capsules containing scolices.
    - B: Small adult worm living in dog intestine.

= Phylum Mesozoa (中生动物门)

- Minute, ciliated, wormlike parasites of marine invertebrates.
- Simple organization: 20-30 cells in two layers (not homologous to germ layers).
- *Rhombozoa* (菱形虫纲): Parasites in cephalopod kidneys. Adults called *vermiforms* (蠕虫形).
- *Orthonectida* (直泳虫纲): Parasites of brittle stars, molluscs, etc.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-25").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-25").caption
)
- *Mesozoan reproduction*: Shows asexual production of vermiform larvae and sexual production of infusoriform larvae in Rhombozoa.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-26").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-26").caption
)
- *Orthonectid*: *Rhopalura* showing the simple structure of ciliated cells surrounding sex cells.

= Phylum Nemertea (纽形动物门)

- Also called *Rhynchocoela* (吻腔动物).
- Bilaterally symmetrical, triploblastic.
- *Proboscis* (吻): Long muscular tube in a fluid-filled cavity (*rhynchocoel* (吻腔)) above the gut; eversible to capture prey.
- *Complete digestive system*: Mouth and anus.
- *Circulatory system*: Closed loop system.
- *Reproduction*: Mostly dioecious; some species produce a ciliated *pilidium* (帽状幼虫) larva.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-27").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-27").caption
)
- *Ribbon worm*: *Amphiporus* showing the extended proboscis.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-28").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-28").caption
)
- *Proboscis mechanism*:
    - A: Proboscis extended to catch prey.
    - B: Diagram showing the rhynchocoel above the digestive tract and the stylet on the proboscis.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-29").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-29").caption
)
- *Large nemerteans*: *Baseodiscus* can reach several meters in length.

#figure(
  image(images.at("figure-14-30").path, width: 50%),
  caption: images.at("figure-14-30").caption
)
- *Nemertean anatomy*:
    - A: Cross section showing rhynchocoel, proboscis, and gut.
    - B: Excretory (flame bulbs) and circulatory systems closely associated.
